Stack Overflow Survey 2020 Data Analysis¶

  • Analyzing responses from the Stack Overflow Developer Survey 2020
  • Using Pandas, Numpy, Matplotlib and Seaborn libraries
  • Asking and answering questions
  • Drawing inferences and conclusions

The dataset contains over 64,000 responses to 60 questions. The responses have been anonymized and there's no personally identifiable information available although each respondant has been assigned a randomized respondant ID.

Data Preparation and Cleaning¶

Since the survey responses contain a wealth of information, the analysis will be done on the follwing areas only:

  • Demographics of the survey respondents & the global programming community
  • Distribution of programming skills, experience and preferences
  • Employment-related information, preferences & opinions

Now let's select a subset of columns with relevent data for the analysis

In [17]:

Only two of the columns were detected as numeric columns(Age and WorkWeekHrs) while other are of object data type, even though there are a few other columns which have mostly numeric values. To make analysis easier, let's convert some other columns intro numeric data types, while ignoring any non-numeric value(they will get converted to NaNs)

In [26]:
survey_df['Age1stCode'] = pd.to_numeric(survey_df.Age1stCode, errors='coerce')
survey_df['YearsCode'] = pd.to_numeric(survey_df.YearsCode, errors='coerce')
survey_df['YearsCodePro'] = pd.to_numeric(survey_df.YearsCodePro, errors='coerce')

There seems to be a problem with the age column, as the minimum value is 1 and the maximum is 279. This can be a common issue with surveys: responses may contain invalid values due to accidental or intentional errors while responding. A simple fix would be to ignore the rows where the age is higher than 100 years or lower than 10 years as invalid survey responses. We can do this using the .drop method.

In [28]:
survey_df.drop(survey_df[survey_df.Age < 10].index, inplace=True)
survey_df.drop(survey_df[survey_df.Age > 100].index, inplace=True)

The same holds for WorkWeekHrs. Let's ignore entries where the value for the column is higher than 140 hours. (~20 hours per day).

In [30]:
survey_df.drop(survey_df[survey_df.WorkWeekHrs > 140].index, inplace=True)

Exploratory Analysis and Visualization¶

Before we ask questions about the survey responses, it would helpful to understand the respondents' demographics, i.e., country, age, gender, education level, employment level, etc. We will explore these variables to understand how representative the survey is of the worldwide programming community.

Let's begin by importing matplotlib.pyplot and seaborn.

In [36]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

sns.set_style('darkgrid')
matplotlib.rcParams['font.size'] = 14
matplotlib.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (9, 5)
matplotlib.rcParams['figure.facecolor'] = '#00000000'

From the bar chart, it appears that high number of respondents are from the US and India.

Age¶

The distribution of respondents' age is another crucial factor to look at. We can use a histogram to visualize it.

In [42]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.title(schema.Age)
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Number of respondents')

plt.hist(survey_df.Age, bins=np.arange(10,80,5), color='purple');

It appears that a large percentage of respondents are 20-40 years old. It's somewhat representative of the programming community in general.

Education Level¶

Let's compare the education levels of respondents to gain some insight into this. Let's use a horizontal bar plot here.

In [47]:
sns.countplot(y=survey_df.EdLevel)
plt.xticks(rotation=75);
plt.title(schema['EdLevel'])
plt.ylabel(None);

It appears that well over half of the respondents hold a bachelor's or master's degree, so most programmers seem to have some college education. However, it's not clear from this graph alone if they hold a degree in computer science.

Let's also plot undergraduate majors, but this time we'll convert the numbers into percentages and sort the values to make it easier to visualize the order.

In [48]:
schema.UndergradMajor
Out[48]:
'What was your primary field of study?'
In [49]:
undergrad_pct = survey_df.UndergradMajor.value_counts() * 100 / survey_df.UndergradMajor.count()

sns.barplot(x=undergrad_pct, y=undergrad_pct.index)

plt.title(schema.UndergradMajor)
plt.ylabel(None);
plt.xlabel('Percentage');

It turns out that 40% of programmers holding a college degree have a field of study other than computer science.

Employment

Freelancing or contract work is a common choice among programmers, so it would be interesting to compare the breakdown between full-time, part-time, and freelance work. Let's visualize the data from the Employment column.

In [50]:
schema.Employment
Out[50]:
'Which of the following best describes your current employment status?'
In [51]:
(survey_df.Employment.value_counts(normalize=True, ascending=True)*100).plot(kind='barh', color='g')
plt.title(schema.Employment)
plt.xlabel('Percentage');

So, there are majority of people who are employed full-time and almost 10% of people who work as freelancers.

def split_multicolumn(col_series):
    result_df = col_series.to_frame()
    options = []
    # Iterate over the column
    for idx, value  in col_series[col_series.notnull()].iteritems():
        # Break each value into list of options
        for option in value.split(';'):
            # Add the option as a column to result
            if not option in result_df.columns:
                options.append(option)
                result_df[option] = False
            # Mark the value in the option column as True
            result_df.at[idx, option] = True
    return result_df[options]

Q: Which are the most loved languages, i.e., a high percentage of people who have used the language want to continue learning & using it over the next year?

Here, we will use Pandas array operations. We will Create a new data frame languages_loved_df that contains a True value for a language only if the corresponding values in languages_worked_df and languages_interested_df are both True. Then, we'll take the column-wise sum of languages_loved_df and divide it by the column-wise sum of languages_worked_df to get the percentage of respondents who "love" the language. Then,sort the results in decreasing order and plot a horizontal bar graph.

In [65]:
languages_loved_df = languages_worked_df & languages_interested_df
In [67]:
languages_loved_percentages = (languages_loved_df.sum() * 100/ languages_worked_df.sum()).sort_values(ascending=False)
In [68]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
sns.barplot(x=languages_loved_percentages, y=languages_loved_percentages.index)
plt.title("Most loved languages");
plt.xlabel('count');

So, Rust comes out as the most loved langugae among programming community followed by Typescript and the Python.

Inferences and Conclusions¶

We've drawn many inferences from the survey. Here's a summary of them:

  • Based on the survey respondents' demographics, we can infer that the survey is somewhat representative of the overall programming community.The highest number of respondants are from U.S. and India, also 20-40 age category having the highest number of programmers however, it has fewer responses from women & non-binary genders.

  • Although most programmers hold a college degree, a reasonably large percentage did not have computer science as their college major.

  • Although most of the people are employed full time, significant percentage of programmers either work part-time or as a freelancer.

  • Javascript & HTML/CSS are the most used programming languages in 2020, closely followed by SQL & Python.

  • Python is the language most people are interested in learning.

  • Rust and TypeScript are the most "loved" languages in 2020.

  • Programmers worldwide seem to be working for around 40 hours a week on average, with slight variations by country.

  • You can learn and start programming professionally at any age. You're likely to have a long and fulfilling career if you also enjoy programming as a hobby.
